Prolog
"Please, my dear!" Queen Eirwen pleaded, "don't send her away! She is still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. In the eyes of the Ice King, a girl meant weakness. After all, up to this point, he had only fathered sons.
"You have two options: either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is its punishment for your failure, Eirwen," he spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and a never-ending war broke out between the two kingdoms, until eventually the South offered a truce.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"Please, my king, do with me as you will, imprison me, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with full disgust. Perhaps, but only perhaps, would he show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest times and who had given him his sons.
"Alright. The child can stay in the palace," he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's free rooms. Then he commanded the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution square, where all the citizens of the city could witness it.
As the guards escorted them to the execution square, a loud uproar erupted among the citizens when they realized that their only, beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others questioned why this should happen, but all were in agreement.
"Let them go!"
"Why is he doing that to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden pole, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Hangman. The woman who had just been queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king delivered a speech explaining how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and rejected his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Never give up, Kari." This marked the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only one knock could be heard from the room located far to the left in the southern wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was going on in that room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors spread among the maidservants. It was said that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room and was waiting to be let out.
Ivory thought, "Your assumption could not have been more wrong," and walked toward the southern wing, while the servants wandered around and whispered among themselves. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors naturally also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" Ivory whispered before the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered whether, unlike the last time, entry would actually be granted. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was heard from inside, probably to say that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory had walked in without asking.
From within, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "Yes." The coldness and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a noise from what was supposedly an empty room, even though Ivory had entered it for several years.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for her. Everywhere there was paper. Books were scattered around, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay about. There were no windows, and very little or no light at all. In addition, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a blizzard had swept through.
The girl lay curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"What notebook is this?" Ivory asked and sat next to Kari on the bed.
